When you want to specify that your iOS app should only open on certain routes or conditions on your website, you can use the `apple-app-site-association` (AASA) file. Here is an example of how to set up your AASA file to open your app only on certain routes or conditions:

Step 1: Create the AASA File
Create an AASA file named `apple-app-site-association`. The file should be a JSON file with the following structure:
```javascript
{
  "applinks": {
    "apps": [
      {
        "appID": "YOUR_APP_ID",
        "paths": [ "GET /path/*" ]
      }
    ],
    "details": [
      {
        "appID": "YOUR_APP_ID",
        "components": [
          {
            "/path/*": "com.example.app"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```
Replace "YOUR_APP_ID" with the Apple App ID of your app, and replace "com.example.app" with your app's bundle ID. Also replace "path" within the "paths" property with the route you want your app to open on.

Step 2: Add the AASA File to Your Website
Upload the AASA file to your website and place it in the root directory of your website. For example, if your website is hosted on https://example.com/, the AASA file should be located at https://example.com/apple-app-site-association.

Step 3: Test Your Setup
Load your website on a device with your app installed, and click on a link that matches the routes specified in your AASA file. Your app should now launch with the correct data.

If your app does not launch or it does not load the correct data, you can check if there are any SSL or HTTPS certification issues that may be causing the problem. Check your app's entitlements file to ensure that the Associated Domains capability is enabled, and that it includes your website's domain. You can also check if there are any conflicts with other AASA files from other apps on the device,

By creating and implementing an AASA file, you can specify which links on your website should open your iOS app, giving your users a seamless user experience.

